Writing Your First Dockerfile
Dockerfile Instruction Reference
Instruction	Purpose
FROM	Base image (must be first)
WORKDIR	Set working directory inside container
COPY	Copy files from host into image
RUN	Execute commands during build (adds a layer)
ENV	Set environment variables
EXPOSE	Document which port the app uses
CMD	Default command when container starts (overridable)
ENTRYPOINT	Fixed command — CMD becomes its arguments
ARG	Build-time variable (not in final image)
.dockerignore	Exclude files from build context

Hands-On: Dockerize a Python Flask App
Step 1 — Create the App
mkdir ~/docker-python && cd ~/docker-python

cat > app.py <<'EOF'
from flask import Flask
app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route("/")
def home():
    return "Hello from Docker + Python!"

@app.route("/health")
def health():
    return {"status": "ok"}

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(host="0.0.0.0", port=5000)
EOF

cat > requirements.txt <<'EOF'
flask==3.0.0
EOF

Step 2 — Write the Dockerfile
cat > Dockerfile <<'EOF'
# 1. Base image
FROM python:3.11-slim

# 2. Set working directory
WORKDIR /app

# 3. Copy dependencies first (layer cache optimization)
COPY requirements.txt .

# 4. Install dependencies
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

# 5. Copy app source
COPY app.py .

# 6. Document the port
EXPOSE 5000

# 7. Run the app
CMD ["python", "app.py"]
EOF

Step 3 — Add .dockerignore
cat > .dockerignore <<'EOF'
__pycache__/
*.pyc
*.pyo
.env
.git
EOF

Step 4 — Build & Run
# Build image
docker build -t flask-app:v1 .

# Watch the layers build — notice STEP numbers

# Run container
docker run -d --name flask-app -p 5000:5000 flask-app:v1

# Test
curl http://localhost:5000
curl http://localhost:5000/health

# View logs
docker logs flask-app

Step 5 — Observe Layer Caching
# Make a change to app.py only
echo "# comment" >> app.py

# Rebuild — notice steps 1-4 say "CACHED", only step 5+ rebuilds
docker build -t flask-app:v2 .

Hands-On: Dockerize a Node.js App
Step 1 — Create the App
mkdir ~/docker-node && cd ~/docker-node

cat > package.json <<'EOF'
{
  "name": "docker-node-app",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "main": "index.js",
  "dependencies": {
    "express": "^4.18.0"
  }
}
EOF

cat > index.js <<'EOF'
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Hello from Docker + Node.js!');
});

app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'ok', uptime: process.uptime() });
});

app.listen(3000, '0.0.0.0', () => {
  console.log('Server running on port 3000');
});
EOF

Step 2 — Write the Dockerfile
cat > Dockerfile <<'EOF'
FROM node:20-alpine

WORKDIR /app

# Copy package files first (cache optimization)
COPY package*.json ./

# Install dependencies
RUN npm install --production

# Copy source
COPY index.js .

EXPOSE 3000

CMD ["node", "index.js"]
EOF

cat > .dockerignore <<'EOF'
node_modules/
npm-debug.log
.git
EOF

Step 3 — Build & Run
docker build -t node-app:v1 .
docker run -d --name node-app -p 3000:3000 node-app:v1

curl http://localhost:3000
curl http://localhost:3000/health
docker logs node-app

Multi-Stage Build (Production Pattern)
Reduces final image size — build tools not included in runtime image.
cat > Dockerfile.multistage <<'EOF'
# Stage 1: Build
FROM node:20 AS builder
WORKDIR /app
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install
COPY . .

# Stage 2: Runtime (tiny image)
FROM node:20-alpine AS runtime
WORKDIR /app
COPY --from=builder /app/node_modules ./node_modules
COPY --from=builder /app/index.js .
EXPOSE 3000
CMD ["node", "index.js"]
EOF

docker build -f Dockerfile.multistage -t node-app:slim .
docker images node-app        # compare sizes

Interview Questions & Answers
Q1. What is the purpose of WORKDIR?

Sets the working directory for subsequent instructions and the running container. Creates it if it doesn't exist. Avoids hardcoded paths like RUN cd /app && ....

Q2. Difference between CMD and ENTRYPOINT?

CMD is the default command — easily overridden: docker run image custom-cmd.
ENTRYPOINT is fixed — always runs. CMD becomes arguments to it.
Together: ENTRYPOINT ["python"] + CMD ["app.py"] → runs python app.py, but docker run image other.py → runs python other.py.

Q3. Difference between RUN, CMD, and ENTRYPOINT?

RUN executes at build time — installs packages, creates files.
CMD/ENTRYPOINT execute at run time — start the application.

Q4. Why copy requirements.txt before app.py?

Layer caching. If only app code changes, Docker reuses the cached dependency layer — no re-download of packages. If you copy everything at once, any change invalidates the dependency layer.

Q5. What is .dockerignore?

Like .gitignore — tells Docker which files to exclude from build context. Reduces build context size and prevents leaking secrets or unnecessary files.

Q6. What is a multi-stage build? Why use it?

Multiple FROM stages in one Dockerfile. Build tools (compilers, npm dev-deps) stay in the build stage. Only the runtime artifact is copied to the final lean image. Reduces image size and attack surface.

Q7. What is build context?

The directory sent to the Docker daemon during docker build. Everything in that directory is available to COPY. Keep it small with .dockerignore.

Q8. What does --no-cache-dir do in pip install?

Tells pip not to cache downloaded packages, reducing image size.

Q9. Why use EXPOSE?

Documents which port the app listens on. Does NOT actually publish it — you still need -p host:container in docker run. Used by orchestration tools like Kubernetes.

Q10. What is the difference between COPY and ADD?

COPY copies local files only — explicit and predictable.
ADD can extract .tar.gz and fetch URLs — avoid unless needed. Prefer COPY.
